{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6b904a00-7aee-48ef-8286-1a47276f9910","content":"This is a **TUnit** project using Microsoft.Testing.Platform. TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` (not `--filter`). The command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter uses a path hierarchy (`/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`), so `/**/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches all tests inside the `SmsNotificationTests` class regardless of assembly or namespace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4c9d49da-f83a-43d6-8dd4-08dd714950e0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax uses `--treenode-filter` rather than `--filter`.\n\nThe TUnit treenode filter syntax for filtering by class is:\n```\n/**/*SmsNotificationTests*\n```\n\nThe command would be:\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/*SmsNotificationTests*\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. The filter for MTP with TUnit uses `--treenode-filter`. The syntax is a path-like pattern:\n\n\n`/**/<ClassName>/<MethodName>`\n\nTo filter by class name `SmsNotificationTests`:\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nActually, let me reconsider the TUnit treenode filter syntax. The treenode filter in TUnit uses a hierarchical path: `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`\n\nTo match the class `SmsNotificationTests`:\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nI need to be more precise about the exact syntax for the treenode filter pattern. Finalizing the filter pattern...","outputTokens":666,"requestId":"1BC4:19082:4D7BAC:583AA6:6A03D685"},"id":"640c50b2-8b5a-4c88-9222-644d5ad3c577","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:40:37.258Z","parentId":"d949df5e-0a50-4cfd-8a37-9e173b2175bb"}
